name: 2-(boc-amino)pyridine
Reason: The prediction of the melting point for 2-(boc-amino)pyridine can be estimated by considering the functional groups present in the molecule and their expected influence on the melting point. The basic pyridine unit has a melting point around -42 degrees Celsius. The addition of a boc (tert-butoxycarbonyl) group significantly increases the molecular weight and steric hindrance, which tends to raise the melting point. A large aliphatic boc group could raise the melting point by around +100 to +130 degrees Celsius compared to pyridine. The amino group substituted at the 2-position can also affect melting point through hydrogen bonding capacity, though in this protected (boc-amino) form, the hydrogen bonding is less pronounced compared to a free amino group. The amino group might increase the melting point by about +10 to +20 degrees Celsius due to potential for intermolecular interactions. The aromatic nature and planarity of the pyridine ring may also facilitate pi-pi stacking interactions, which could further contribute to a higher melting point, potentially adding another +20 to +30 degrees Celsius.
